text: She only did 1000 miles of a 2650 mile trail.  Robert Redford is playing Bill Bryson (Walk in the Woods) but he only did 870 miles of 2179 miles of AT. Lot of hype and inspiration from people who are basically not very impressive. I know, I solo hiked the whole AT along with the few others who completed the journey end to end. The real challenges come after the 1/2 way point and the magic of really getting to know who you are comes in the last few hundred miles when a lot of people start quitting and you think you are crazy to keep going on and you do it anyways.  Not to say 1000 miles is not impressive, nor 870.  But thousands do that each year.  Only hundreds actually make it.

This story besides "into the wild" is about a women that wants to become a better person and reborn after all the mistakes that she made, "into the wild" is about a guy who hates the system and the way people live their lifes and wants to be find true happiness in the beauty of mother nature. So, If you guys want to think this is a copy "into the wild", go ahead, but you might have a little of information first in your hands if your comment wants to be taken seriously.  *If you don't agree "into the wild" it's about what I said, It's ok, we can all have different opinions and interpretations about something.

text: Sometimes the time on the trail and the bringing of issues good and bad with you are the constant.  Nature is simply there. First went on this trail in 1974 with my wife to be...started from the north and did not complete.  Now 40 years later and with life changes heading on the trail again.  Thanks to all that helped every hiker on this trail,  Looking forward to seeing this film as I did seeing the latest film on walking the Camino in Spain,   Time as I've known it doesn't take much time to pass by me. Minutes into days, turn into months turn into years, they hurry by me. Still I love to see the sun go down and the world go around.  Dreams full of promises, hopes for the future I've had many. Dreams I can't remember now, hopes that I've forgotten, faded memories. Still I love to see the sun go down and the world go around.  And I love to see the morning as it steals across the sky, I love to remember and I love to wonder why, and I hope that I'm around so I can be there when I die, when I'm gone.  I hope that you will think of me in moments when you're happy and you're smiling. that the thought will comfort you on cold and cloudy days if you are crying. And that you'll love to see the sun go down and the world go around and around and around.  "Time as I know it, doesn't take much time to pass by me."  John Denver.

text: it makes me so happy to see a movie like this with a female lead. After reading Into The Wild when I was 18, I spent 2 years saving money so that I could leave England and go hitchhiking and living out of a backpack without the need to beg or survive on charity- I wanted to fund the whole thing independently. Over 9 months I hiked across France, Switzerland, Germany and Italy, and then I spent 3 months hitchhiking/hiking across America. As a young female doing this entirely by myself, it was scary, lonely and I was constantly under fire from people saying 'young women shouldn't be doing this kind of thing' and it would get to points where I started to believe them. There's no real role models for girls on the road, and I never once bumped into another girl to gain advice or support from. Films (and books) like this are so important.

text: Did multi-month and shorter journeys akin to this (backpacking in National Parks and Forests - mainly in the west) when I was young both in the USA and in Southern Europe.  Did a lot of hitch-hiking on highways and sleeping in train stations in cities, camping ALL OVER the place, in parks, on farmland, on the edges of towns, next to creeks etc.... At that time there were very few solo women backpackers (1980"s).  I travelled both alone and with a girlfriend.   Would I recommend it to women (or men)?   It's pretty darned tough. Not a romantic idealized journey but a test of your strength, a test of your determination, a test of your will.  It most definitely builds character.   Being in nature is very inspiring.  You get to see amazing vistas, wildlife and commune with nature in the most intimate way. You get VERY fit physically and VERY strong mentally.  It helps A LOT to have a meditation practice and to practice prayer (there will be situations in which you will be crying out to God for help).   Perhaps the most dangerous part of travelling is the encounter with the occasional psycho - not so much in National Parks, on trails etc but on the road (especially truck drivers). Sex obsessed truck drivers (and others) who are potentially rapists (I know women who got raped while hitch-hiking in America AND in Europe.  That, I would say is the greatest danger for women.  (Most people you meet are actually very kind and generous).   Another very real danger is bears.  They will take ALL your food if you're not careful.  In Montana and in Canada and Alaska, you have to be very aware of Grizzly Bears.  They are potentially dangerous and you could be mauled and/or killed. Pepper spray is a must as is general Bear awareness.  For any women or men inspired by this film to try a journey like this my advice is:  Start small and start local.  Find a nearby national park and take a 3-4 day backpacking trip.  Once you're comfortable with that, then try a week long trip, then a two week trip etc.   Also, do it while young.  The older you get, the harder it becomes to take journeys like this.   If you do this kind of travel, you'll treasure it for the rest of your days.

text: Wow, I'm very disappointed in some of these comments reflecting people's belief that this movie is just a rip-off of Into the Wild. They are completely different movies, and each is excellent in its own way. Into the Wild is a movie about a kid who graduated from Emory University as a successful student and athlete, but decided to donate all of his material possessions to charity and live in the wild to find spiritual awakening. The entire premise of the movie, however, is that despite the spiritual awareness he finds in the wilderness, he identifies that happiness can best be cultivated with others, not alone. Wild is the story of Cheryl Strayed, who after the death of her mother and spending years of risky behavior, decides to make the bold decision of walking the PCT trail on the west coast. She does this for a number of reasons––to heal, to find herself again, to reflect, to live. Flashbacks permeate the film, telling the story of the relationship between Sheryl and the people who have populated her life. It is a movie about redemption, reflection, and adversity. While I understand the outward appearance of significant similarities between the movies, the thematic elements of both are quite different.

text: I just listened to the audio version of the original book WILD by Cheryl Strayed, and now i just HAVE to buy this movie! I've read some of the comments her about how the movie is a rip off of Into the Wild and no it isn't. I have not seen the whole movie yet, but it is taken from the ACTUAL story of a REAL person going through real life trauma after her mother died. These days we would call it PTSS or similar. She just had to get away from stupid people who make stupid remarks, and burn herself out physically till she could reach some peace and resolution within herself. If that looks like it is copying someone else, think about it!! That means there are other people going through trauma too and having to get away from humankind to "lick their wounds".  Some write, some paint, some go do something physical they have not done before. The ones who don't actively deal with their stress can end up cracking up and damaging people or property to get revenge on the world. So good on these people who go off and have an experience on their own till they can deal with everything.

text: I'm so happy... That's one of my dreams to travel alone ... no responsibilities..to discover the world myself..on my own.. this movie is so important. i watched it two days back and I can't stop thinking about it since.  I travelled in a airplane for the first time when I was 16 and that was all by myself. Flying over 1800 Km without a family member and that too for the first time. in the airport I met a girl. On talking to her I got to know she was traveling alone. She came from Israel, (probably hiked) through Vietnam and a few other countries and then came to Delhi, India (where I live) and then she was traveling to Mumbai and then back home.  Her name is Mikka (idk if I'm spelling this correct) but it was lovely to know she was traveling all by herself. After I told her that I was traveling alone too and I was just 16, she was so happy and asked me to take care and have a safe flight.  She was 20 btw.

text: I read this book when I was in the process of coming to terms with and ending a very toxic, emotionally abusive relationship. It was so cathartic to read while I was figuring out what love meant and what it didn’t, and what I am worth and what love I am worthy of. It took me a few months,  of intense fighting and being pulled back in, of questioning my own thoughts and decisions. I slowly worked my way through the book simultaneously. I left the last chapter for after I left him. Immediately after, Ill never forget sitting on my bedroom floor, screaming and screaming my throat raw and hot tears searing down my face. I could not breathe. I was terrified because I finally had let him go, and along with him all my notions about myself. I had deemed myself unworthy and now needed to find my worth and learn to love myself. My lungs hurt. I finished the book. I saw hope.
